observations.recommendation:
We recommended management the following:

The Municipal Treasurer in coordination with the Municipal Assessor to conduct reconciliation of records in order to update the taxpayer’s index card particularly on assessed value of real properties and other relevant data. Thereafter, reconciliation shall be made regularly at the close of each year;

The Municipal Treasurer to maintain a readily available monitoring flatform matching every collection made with the corresponding year of receivable;

The Municipal Accountant to extend the analysis made and come up with a schedule showing the details of RPT/SET receivable on a yearly basis;

The Municipal Accountant to make a subsidiary ledger (SL) for RPT/SET receivable using the year when the receivable was recorded as code starting CY 2023;

Reconciliation of record between the monitoring schedule prepared by the Office of the Municipal Treasurer and SL prepared by the Office of the Municipal Accountant at the close of each year; and

The Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary adjusting entry to correct the overstatement of RPT/SET receivable and corresponding overstatement of Deferred Real Property Tax Income/Deferred Special Education Tax Income.

Recommendations:
We recommended and Management agreed to comply the following:
Assess whether there is a need to reconstitute the composition of the Inventory Committee to ensure that the task shall be completed;
Conduct the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances in accordance with the guidelines and procedures set forth in COA Circular No. 2020-006;
Prepare of the Report on Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE) using the prescribed format upon completion of the physical count and furnish the Auditor concerned with the copy thereafter; and
Conduct reconciliation between inventory count per RPCPPE and property and accounting records, as warranted.

We recommended management the following:

Preparation of schedule/list of delinquent taxes broken down on a yearly basis which remained uncollected or unpaid as of December 31, 2022;

Issuance of Notice of Delinquency relative to the unpaid real property tax / special education tax in accordance with Section 254 of R.A. No. 7160 and Section 150(1)a, Book IV of the LTOM;

Issuance of Warrant of Levy in accordance with Section 258 of R.A. No. 7160 Section 150(1)b, Book IV of the LTOM; and

Submission of the schedule/list of delinquent taxes including a statement of the reason/s for such non-collection or non-payment to the Sangguniang Bayan requesting for assistance in the enforcement of the remedies for collection in accordance with Section 269 of R.A. No. 7160.

The Head of the Agency to create an Inventory Committee composed of adequate number of members to be able complete the physical inventory in three months or less. The committee shall also have at least one member each from the Accounting and Property Divisions/Units;

The Inventory Committee conduct inventory taking activities according to previously approved Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) and prepare the RPCPPE upon completion of the physical count, using the prescribed format under the Accounting Manual and submit the same not later than January 31 of the ensuing; 

Moving forward to the implementation of the Government Accounting Manual for LGUs volume II to follow the prescribed forms and reports described in sections 61 to 74 as illustrated in Appendices 54 to 67 of the manual. And to submit the same in accordance with GAM for LGUs volume I, section 266 not later than January 31 of the ensuing year; 

The Property Unit and Accounting Unit undertake collaborative procedures to ensure that all PPEs included in the RPCPPE are duly recorded in their respective records and that the Property Cards (PCs) maintained by the Property Unit and the PPE Ledger Cards (PPELCs) maintained by the Accounting Unit are reconciled; Moving forward to the implementation of the GAM for LGU follow the pertinent rules as described in volume 1, section 269; and 

The management undertake disposition procedures for non-existing/missing PPEs and derecognition procedures of non-existing/missing PPE without available record of accountability as provided for in COA Circular No. 2020-006.

The Municipal Treasurer to conduct the physical inventory of the Biological Asset; 

The Municipal Accountant to reclassify the account to its proper asset account and to reconcile with the records of the Municipal Treasurer; and 
Moving forward to the implementation of the Government Accounting Manual for LGUs, Biological Assets transactions are to be in accordance with Sections 304 to 315.

Direct the Municipal Accountant to strictly observe the rules and regulations on the preparation of the financial statements; 

Also, the Municipal Accountant to revisit the provisions of the International Public Sector Accounting Standards (IPSAS) 2 and other COA issuances particularly on the preparation and presentation of accounts in the financial statements.

Moving forward to the issuance of the Government Accounting Manual for LGUs, to strictly follow the proforma illustrations for the Notes to the Financial Statements.

The Municipality to coordinate with the provider of the Accounting System and impose the following:
Correct the internal issues presented by the computer system, and make a patch to improve the existing system;

Request that continuous customer support be easily available whenever issues were presented;

Provide a user manual and incorporate it in the system where any user could access it in case they need help in using the system. If the updating of SL feature is not yet available, then the provider must incorporate it in the system since it is very important in an accounting system; and

Provide safety features in the system. All users of the system and the changes they made must be properly monitored. Users must be provided with certain level of authority as to their capability to access forms, reports, query, and/ or tables.

Recommendations
We recommended management the following:
direct the liquidating officer to locate the notice given by the bank relative to the returned checks;
if the documents cannot be found, make representation with the bank, requesting for the copy of the said notice or any equivalent documents;
direct the municipal accountant in coordination with the liquidating office to trace the cash deposit as a replacement of the returned checks; and
direct the municipal accountant to prepare the necessary adjustment, as warranted based on the documents presented.

Recommendations
We recommended management the following:
Coordination between the Office of the Municipal Accountant, Office of the Municipal Engineer and the Office of the Bids and Awards Committee to locate the pertinent documents to support the issuance of Certificate of Completion relative to the above-listed projects (e.g. contract agreement, program of works; disbursement vouchers pertaining to progress billings);
The Municipal Accountant to conduct a thorough analysis based on the documents secured as a result of the coordinated efforts between the two offices;
The Office of the Municipal Engineer in coordination with the Office of the Audit Team Leader to conduct ocular inspection relative to the above-listed projects to ascertain its completion;
The Office of the Municipal Engineer to cause the preparation of Certificate of Completion if duly substantiated with documents and verified to be completed based on the Program of Works as a result of the ocular inspection;
The Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary entry to close the CIP account and record the completed project to its appropriate asset account upon issuance of the Certificate of Completion; and
The Municipal Accountant to set-up the corresponding depreciation expense and accumulated depreciation thereafter.

Recommendations
We recommended management to strictly adhere with the standard operation procedures prescribed under the Manual on the New Government Accounting System for LGUs by:
establishing of cut-off time, to give way for the preparation of RCD and other supporting documents;
directing all collectors to accomplish the RCD before the close of each business day and turn over the collection to the liquidating officer;
directing the liquidating officer to accomplish the RCD daily and forward the collections together with the accompanying documents (e.g. validated deposit slips and duplicate copy of accountable forms) to the municipal treasurer;
directing the municipal treasurer to deposit intact all collections based on the RCD forwarded by the liquidating officer bearing its name as the depositor;
directing the municipal treasurer to forward the RCD together with the supporting documents (e.g. validated deposit slips and duplicate copy of accountable forms) to the Office of the Municipal Accountant daily; and
directing the municipal accountant to stop the practice of preparing a one-time JEV for the recording of collections instead prepare an individual JEV for each RCD together with its supporting documents.

The Municipal Treasurer to submit timely the list of delinquent Business Taxpayers to the Municipal accountant to be used in the computation and recording of the business taxes; 

The Municipal Accountant to record the business taxes earned during the period; and

The Municipal Accountant record the business taxes earned for the next period.

The Municipal Accountant to evaluate the liabilities of the Municipality and determine the causes of the unreconciled amounts; 

Further, identify these liabilities and properly classify them to their respective accounts; and 

Follow the basic accounting principle on the recognition of liabilities and make the necessary correcting entries.

The Local Chief Executive to file a request for authority to write-off dormant receivable accounts and unliquidated cash advances to the COA Audit Team Leader and/or Supervising Auditor;

The Municipal Accountant prepare the aging of dormant receivables and unliquidated cash advances to support the request for write-off and prepare the necessary JEV in the event that the request for authority to write-off accounts is granted; and

Conduct regular monitoring and analysis of receivable accounts to ensure that these are collected when these become due and demandable and that cash advances are liquidated within the prescribed period.

the Local Chief Executive to direct the Municipal Accountant to strictly observe the rules and regulations on the preparation of the financial statements;

Also, the Municipal Accountant to revisit the provisions of the International Public Sector Accounting Standards (IPSAS) and other COA issuances particularly on the preparation and presentation of restated financial statements; and 

Moving forward to the implementation of the Government Accounting Manual for LGUs, future restatements are to be in accordance with Sections 246 and 247.

The Municipal Accountant to provide a working schedule to support the entries made to entity difference;

Further, stop the usage of a balancing figures to reconcile the difference between the actual amounts presented in the SCBAA and the amount in the Statement of Financial Performance; and 

Moving forward to the issuance of the Government Accounting Manual for LGUs, the Municipal Accountant will now be responsible for the recording of obligations, to properly list and monitor possible charges which can be considered as entity, basis and Timing differences in order to prevent the usage of a balancing figure.

The Local Chief Executive to revise the Four-Day compressed work week in order to properly provide the required one-hour lunch break;

Further, for the month of May, charge against all the VL days of all the Municipal Employees; and  

Also, when drafting matters concerning Human Resources, the Human Resource Management Officer to consult with the Civil Service Commission in order to prevent misinterpretations.

